<p><b>Nepal Bhasa</b> (<span lang="new" xml:lang="new">नेपाल भाषा</span>, also known as <i><b>Newah Bhaye</b></i> and <i><b>Newari</b></i>) is one of the major languages of <a href="/wiki/Nepal" title="Nepal">Nepal</a>, and is also spoken in <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a>, particularly in <a href="/wiki/Sikkim" title="Sikkim">Sikkim</a> where it is one of the 11 official languages.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> Nepal Bhasa is the mother tongue of about 3% of the people in Nepal (see the list of <a href="/wiki/Languages_of_Nepal" title="Languages of Nepal">languages of Nepal</a>). It is one of roughly five hundred <a href="/wiki/Sino-Tibetan_languages" title="Sino-Tibetan languages">Sino-Tibetan languages</a>, and belongs to the <a href="/wiki/Tibeto-Burman" title="Tibeto-Burman" class="mw-redirect">Tibeto-Burman</a> branch of this family. It is spoken mainly by the <a href="/wiki/Newar" title="Newar" class="mw-redirect">Newars</a>, who chiefly inhabit the towns of the <a href="/wiki/Kathmandu_Valley" title="Kathmandu Valley">Kathmandu Valley</a>. Although Nepal Bhasa is classified as a Sino-Tibetan language, it has been greatly influenced by the Indo-Aryan languages.</p>
